The HIP 109384 Exoplanetary System


Overview

HIP 109384 is a star with 0.78 times the mass of the Sun, and NaN times its radius. It is located 192.30 light years away from the solar system.

HIP 109384 is known to have 1 exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the HIP 109384 system


HIP 109384 b

HIP 109384 b was discovered by the Haute-Provence Observatory observatory, in 2016-04, using the radial velocity method. Its semi-major axis is 1.13 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of HIP 109384 b is 496.080 times the mass of Earth. The radius of HIP 109384 b is 13.500 that of Earth. At more than 50 Earth masses, HIP 109384 b is a gas giant, a planet whose mass is mostly made up of hydrogen and helium, like Jupiter and Saturn in our solar system.
